\f0\fs28 \cf0 We\'92ve seen that one of the key concepts of Scrivener is that you work on your manuscript in pieces, but this wouldn\'92t be much use if you couldn\'92t put Humpty together again. That\'92s where 
\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f2\b Compile
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0\fs28  comes in: you write your manuscript in the Draft folder, and when you\'92re ready to share it with the world, you \'93compile\'94 it into a single file. Compiling doesn\'92t affect the original documents inside Scrivener\'97they all stay as they were in the Draft folder\'97it simply copies them into a combined text in the form of an e-book, a PDF file, a Word file, a print-out, or whatever format you choose.\

