\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_H::1><$Scr_Ps::0>
\f0\b\fs36 Creating Your Own Compile Formats
\b0\fs28 \cf0 \
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_H::1><!$Scr_Ps::0>
\f0\fs28 Scrivener comes with a number of Compile formats built-in. If they don\'92t provide what you need, you can create your own, as follows:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	1.	}Click on the \'93+\'94 button below the Formats list.\
{\listtext	2.	}If you want to create a new format from scratch, select \'93New Format\'85\'94.\
{\listtext	3.	}If you want to base your new format on an existing one, select \'93Duplicate & Edit Format\'85\'94.\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 At this point, the entire window changes to present you with a wealth of options. Here you can name the format, choose where to save it, create your own section layouts, determine the size of the printed page, set up page headers and footers, override styles, and much, much more. You have complete control over how your work will look when compiled.\
The gear button above the list on the left allows you to set the file formats that will work with your Compile format. The \'93Test\'85\'94 button allows you to test your settings.\
We won\'92t go into all the details of creating your own Compile format here\'97the chances are that you will never need to create your own format and will only use the formats built into Scrivener. For now, it\'92s only important to know that you 
\i can
\i0  create your own formats if you ever need to. Refer to the user manual (available from the 
\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f2\b Help
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0\fs28  menu) if you ever decide to get your fingers dirty (or just experiment\'97you can\'92t break anything!).\
Okay, we\'92re about done. Select \'93Creating a New Project\'94 under \'93Get Going\'94 (expanding the latter if necessary).}